more imagined than real and was enmeshed within widely held cultural signifiers and myths. British Imperialism in Cyprus fills a gap in the existing literature on the early British period in Cyprus and challenges the received and monolithic view that British imperial policy was based primarily or exclusively on strategic-military considerations. The combination of archival research, cultural analysis and visual narrative that makes for an enjoyable read for academics and students of Imperial, British and European history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish economic policy.  aBritish imperial policy.  aBritish imperialism.  aBritish rule.  aCyprus.  aEldorado.  aHellenic nationalism.  aRomantic adventure.  aUnion Jack.  aexpendable backwater.  aimperial asset.  amulticulturalism.  aspiritual imperialism.  astrategic-militarism.  awestern Asia.1 aVarnava, Andrekos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611873840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526118738423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526118738/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles